# Node.js Backend Conventions

## Structure
- Keep route definitions thin — business logic lives in service files, not route handlers
- Layer: `routes/` → `services/` → `repositories/` (data access)
- One responsibility per file — a route file only wires endpoints

## Error Handling
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — typed error response
class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(public statusCode: number, message: string) { super(message) }
}

// ❌ BAD — string throw, untyped catch
throw 'not found'
```
- Always return structured error responses: `{ error: string; code?: string }`
- Use a central error handler middleware — never handle errors inline in routes

## Validation
- Validate all incoming request bodies with `zod` before touching business logic
- Return 400 with validation details on schema failure — never 500 for user input errors

## Environment
- Never hardcode secrets or config — use `process.env` with a validated config module
- Validate env vars at startup using `zod` — fail fast if required vars are missing

## Security
- Sanitize user input — never pass raw user strings to queries or shell commands
- Set CORS explicitly — never use `cors()` without an allowed origins list in production
